{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/terminal-multiplexers-to-the-rescue-218e5394fd95", "time": 1683016882.807456, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/terminal-multiplexers-to-the-rescue-218e5394fd95/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Terminal Multiplexers to the Rescue | by Shivangi Sareen | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Terminal Multiplexers to the Rescue", "description": "A terminal multiplexer is a program that allows users to split a single terminal into one or more virtual sessions. For example, you may want to open Vim in one, and execute a command in another\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/customising-vim-to-get-the-best-out-of-it-part-2-931246996458", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 2}], "all_paragraphs": ["A terminal multiplexer is a program that allows users to split a single terminal into one or more virtual sessions. For example, you may want to open Vim in one, and execute a command in another. This can be achieved by opening new terminal tabs but it still doesn\u2019t achieve that level of parallelism. Terminal multiplexers allow us to run programs side by side, in a single view.", "Terminal multiplexers like tmux lets us split a single terminal session into windows and panes. Panes split a window into multiple instances allowing us to execute processes simultaneously. We can even attach and detach such sessions.", "tmux is highly configurable. Like for Vim we had a .vimrc dotfile, tmux can be customised using the .tmux.conf file. Also, since dealing with dotfiles, it\u2019s great practice to version control them. Check out a very brief article on source controlling and symlinking dotfiles here.", "By default, tmux commands start with a CTRL b, also written as <C-b>, followed by another key. <C-b> is the prefix key followed by the command key. The prefix isn\u2019t an ideal key combination, as keys are too far away on the keyboard, but can easily reconfigured. Reconfiguring it to <C-a> is one of the most common mappings.", "Note the prefix key is pressed first, released and then the command key is pressed.", "Another command that isn\u2019t so fitting by default is when we want to split a window horizontally or vertically. By default:", "Instead of the \" and %, I\u2019ve configured it to | and - to split horizontally and vertically respectively. Much more intuitive.", "The below remapping is added to tmux.conf.", "The above is just a quick glimpse of tmux\u2019s personalisation. There\u2019s a lot more that can be customised!", "Here\u2019s a quick list for all the basic commands for tmux.", "Try and make a habit out of naming your sessions and windows. This has really helped me organise my terminal and kept me from unnecessarily stressing out about where\u2019s the session which has what window.", "I\u2019ve been having a great time working with tmux. As I\u2019m looking into it more, I\u2019m coming across some really amazing stuff that can be done with it. Hopefully, this gets you started!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Software Engineer @Apple | Reader | Writer | The Sustainable Edit"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F218e5394fd95&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fterminal-multiplexers-to-the-rescue-218e5394fd95&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fterminal-multiplexers-to-the-rescue-218e5394fd95&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "http